%%TITLE
Association of HPV infections with second primary tumors in early-staged oral cavity cancer.
%%ABSTRACT
The infection of human papilloma virus (HPV) has been reported in head and neck cancer; however, the clinical significance of HPV infection on the pathogenesis of oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC) is still uncertain.The study recruited 103 patients with pathological early-stage OSCC between March 1997 and December 2003 from Chang Gung Memorial Hospital, Taiwan. Tumor specimens were HPV-genotyped by the EasychipVR HPV Blot method. Clinical association study was performed by using chi-square, Kaplan-Meier, and logrank tests.Thirty-one patients (30.1%) were positive for HPV infection. The most frequent HPV types were types 16 (16 patients, 51.6%) and 18 (seven patients, 22.6%). HPV infection was not associated with tumor aggressiveness (pathological tumor stage or differentiation status), risk exposure (alcohol, cigarette, or areca quid chewing habit), or the treatment outcome (disease-free survival or overall survival). However, infection with HPV-18 was associated with the occurrence of a second primary cancers (Pâ€ƒ=â€ƒ0.033), indicating the infection of HPV in OSCC enhances the susceptibility of developing secondary malignancy.There are 30% of the patients with OSCC infected with HPV, with most high-risk types. HPV-18 infection may enhance the susceptibility of second primary tumors. Large scale of validation study will be needed to confirm this result.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patients, tissue specimens, and clinical diagnosis
This study was approved by the Institutional Review Board of Chang Gung Memorial Hospital. We recruited
103 patients with pathological early-stage oral cavity cancer who had been treated between March 1997 and December 2003 at Chang Gung Memorial Hospital, Lin-Kuo, Taiwan. The mean age of the 103 recruited patients was 49.4 years (range, 26–81 years) (Table 1). Most tumors were located in the tongue and cheek. Of the 103 tumors, 43 (41.7%) were stage I and 60 (58.3%) were stage II. The median follow-up period was 41 months. All patients provided written informed consent for their participation and were interviewed (before surgery) by a well-trained interviewer. The questionnaire used in the interview sought information on demographic data and on current behaviors and past histories of cigarette smoking, alcohol drinking, and areca quid chewing. The deﬁnitions of habitual uses are cigarette smoking: over ﬁve packages per week, alcohol drinking: over seven bottles per week, betel quid chewing: over 100 grains per week, continuously uses for over 1 year.
All patients underwent extensive presurgical evalua- tions, which included a medical history and complete physical examination, complete blood count and routine blood biochemistry, CT and ⁄ or MRI scans of the head and neck, chest radiographs, bone scan, and liver

Clinical histological parameters for each patient were scored according to the recommendations of the Association of Directors of Anatomic and Surgical Pathology (ADASP) for the purpose of reporting any specimens containing oral cavity and oropharynx neoplasms (Zarbo et al, 2000). All the patients received radical surgery with curative intent as their primary treatment. Those who received other treatment (such as radiation or chemotherapy) as primary treatment were excluded from our analysis. The deﬁnition for double-cancer or multiple primary tumor in our study is that a tumor that occurs in another subsite separated by a normal mucosa of 2 cm or more of distance to the primary site. The follow-up period ranged from 12 to 136 months (median, 41.5 months). There were 14 cases with local recurrence in which the tumors re-grew in the same tumor subsite of primary lesions. Another 12 patients had second primary tumor during their follow-up time.
Tissue samples and DNA extraction
Ten micrometer sections were cut from the paraﬃn blocks of cancer tissues and collected into 1.5-ml Eppendorf tubes for DNA extraction. To prevent cross-contamination, each block was cut after a thor- ough cleaning of the microtome blade. Paraﬃn-embed- ded samples were placed in xylene for 5 min and centrifuged at 20817 g. DNA was extracted using QIA- amp DNA Mini kits (Qiagen, Valencia, CA, USA). The
quality (ratio of absorbance at 260 nm ⁄ 280 nm) and
quantity (absorbance at 260 nm) of the isolated DNA were determined spectrophotometrically.
HPV genotyping by EasychipVR HPV blot
SPF1 ⁄ GP6t consensus primers were used to amplify a fragment of approximately 184 bp in the L1 open reading frame of HPV (Lai et al, 2007; Chao et al, 2010). The resulting 15-ll amplimers were hybridized with an EasychipVR HPV Blot nylon membrane (King Car, I-Lan, Taiwan; hereafter HPV Blot) (Huang et al, 2006), on which oligonucleotide probes for 38 types of HPV [6, 11, 16, 18, 26, 31, 32, 33, 35, 37, 39, 42, 43, 44,
45, 51, 52, 53, 54, 55, 56, 58, 59, 61, 62, 66, 67, 68, 69, 70,
71 (CP8061), 72, 74, 81 (CP8304), 82 (MM4), 83
(MM7), 84 (MM8), and L1AE5] had been immobilized. E6 type-speciﬁc PCRs were performed to validate multiple types. Viral characteristics (HPV genotype, high-risk or low-risk type and multiple or single type) of the infection were included in the analyses. If a patient was infected with both high-risk and low-risk types of HPV, this patient was categorized as high-risk group.
Statistical analysis
The major variables examined were disease-free survival (DFS) and overall survival (OS). Follow-up time was calculated from the date of hospital admission for surgery until the date of death or last contact. Diﬀer- ences between proportions of HPV-infected patients were determined using the chi-square test. Survival curves were constructed using the Kaplan–Meier
